In finance, the '''equivalent annual cost''' ('''EAC''') is the cost per year of owning and operating an asset over its entire lifespan. It is calculated by dividing the [[Net present value|NPV]] of a project by the "present value of [[Annuity (finance theory)|annuity]] factor":
<math> EAC = \frac{NPV}{A_{t,r}}</math>, where <math>{A_{t,r}} = \frac{1 - \frac{1}{(1 + r)^t}}{r}</math>
where r is the annual interest rate and
t is the number of years.
Alternatively, EAC can be obtained by multiplying the NPV of the project by the "loan repayment factor".
EAC is often used as a decision making tool in [[capital budgeting]] when comparing investment projects of unequal lifespans. However, the projects being compared must have equal risk: otherwise, EAC must not be used.{{sfn|Copeland|Weston|1988|p=51}}
The technique was first discussed in 1923 in engineering literature,<ref>{{cite book |last= Fish|first= John Charles Lounsbury|date= 1923|title= Engineering Economics|url= |location= New York|publisher= [[McGraw-Hill]]|page= |asin= B001CZKN9K|edition= 2nd}}, and expanded upon in {{cite book |last= Grant|first= Eugene L.|date= 1930|title= Principles of Engineering Economy|url= |location= New York|publisher= Ronald Press|page= |isbn= }}</ref> and, as a consequence, EAC appears to be a favoured technique employed by [[engineer]]s, while [[accountant]]s tend to prefer [[net present value]] (NPV) analysis.{{sfn|Jones|Smith|1982|p=103}} Such preference has been described as being a matter of professional education, as opposed to an assessment of the actual merits of either method.{{sfn|Jones|Smith|1982|p=108}} In the latter group, however, the [[Society of Management Accountants of Canada]] endorses EAC, having discussed it as early as 1959 in a published [[monograph]]<ref>{{cite book |first= C. Geoffrey|last= Edge|authorlink= |title= The appraisal of capital expenditures|url= http://collectionscanada.gc.ca/ourl/res.php?url_ver=Z39.88-2004&url_tim=2015-11-09T14%3A20%3A58Z&url_ctx_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=11838055&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fcollectionscanada.gc.ca%3Aamicus&lang=eng|year= 1959|publisher= Society of Industrial Accountants of Canada|location= [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]]|ol= 16634923M }}</ref> (which was a year before the first mention of NPV in accounting textbooks).{{sfn|Jones|Smith|1982|p=106}}
==Application== EAC can be used in the following scenarios:
#Assessing alternative projects of unequal lives (where only the costs are relevant) in order to address any built-in bias favouring the longer-term investment.{{sfn|Edge|Irvine|1981|pp=74{{endash}}78}} #Determining the optimum economic life of an asset, through charting the change in EAC that may occur due to the fluctuation of operating costs and salvage values over time.{{sfn|Edge|Irvine|1981|pp=78{{endash}}80}} #Assessing whether leasing an asset would be more economical than purchasing it.<ref>{{cite web|title = Leasing vs. Buying Farm Machinery|url = http://www.agmanager.info/farmmgt/machinery/MF2953.pdf|publisher = Department of Agricultural Economics, [[Kansas State University]]}}</ref> #Assessing whether increased maintenance costs will economically change the useful life of an asset.{{sfn|Edge|Irvine|1981|pp=88{{endash}}89}} #Calculating how much should be invested in an asset in order to achieve a desired result (i.e., purchasing a storage tank with a 20-year life, as opposed to one with a 5-year life, in order to achieve a similar EAC).{{sfn|Edge|Irvine|1981|pp=90{{endash}}91}} #Comparing to estimated annual cost savings, in order to determine whether it makes economic sense to invest.{{sfn|Edge|Irvine|1981|p=94}} #Estimating the cost savings required to justify the purchase of new equipment.{{sfn|Edge|Irvine|1981|p=96}} #Determining the cost of continuing with existing equipment.{{sfn|Edge|Irvine|1981|p=97}} #Where an asset undergoes a major overhaul, and the cost is not fully reflected in salvage values, to calculate the optimum life (i.e., lowest EAC) of holding on to the asset.{{sfn|Edge|Irvine|1981|pp=98{{endash}}99}}
==A practical example== A manager must decide on which machine to purchase, where the cost of capital is 5%:<ref>demonstrated at {{cite web|title=Equivalent Annual Cost |url=http://formularium.org/?go=82 |publisher=formularium.org }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
{| class="wikitable" ! Option ! Machine A ! Machine B |- | Investment cost || $50,000 || $150,000 |- | Expected lifetime || 3 years || 8 years |- | Annual maintenance cost || $13,000 || $7500 |- |Equivalent annual cost || <math>\frac{\$50\,000}{A_{3,5}}+\$13\,000=\$31\,360</math> || <math>\frac{\$150\,000}{A_{8,5}}+\$7\,500=\$30\,708</math> |}
The conclusion is to invest in machine B since it has a lower EAC.
==Canadian context with capital cost allowance== Such analysis can also be carried out on an after-tax basis, and extensive work has been undertaken in Canada for investment appraisal of assets subject to its [[capital cost allowance]] regime for computing depreciation for income tax purposes. It is subject to a three-part calculation:{{sfn|Edge|Irvine|1981|pp=74{{endash}}102}}
#Determination of the after-tax NPV of the investment #Calculation of the after-tax NPV of the operating cost stream #Applying a [[sinking fund]] amortization factor to the after-tax amount of any salvage value.
In mathematical notation, for assets subject to the general half-year rule of CCA calculation, this is expressed as:
<math> EAC = \frac{I \left [ 1-\left (\frac{td}{i+d}\right )\left (\frac{1+\frac{1}{2}i}{1+i}\right ) \right ]}{A_{n,i}} + \frac{1}{A_{n,i}}\sum_{n=0}^{N} \frac{{R_n}\left (1-t\right )}{(1+i)^{n}} - \frac{S \left [ 1-\left (\frac{td}{i+d}\right )\left (\frac{1+\frac{1}{2}i}{1+i}\right ) \right ]}{F_{n,i}}</math>
where:
:''A'' = Capital recovery (amortization) factor :''F'' = Sinking fund amortization factor :''I'' = Investment :''S'' = Estimated salvage value :<math>{R_n}</math> = Operating expense stream :''d'' = CCA rate per year for tax purposes :''t'' = rate of taxation :''n'' = number of years :''i'' = [[cost of capital]], rate of interest, or minimum rate of return (whichever is most relevant)
==Further reading== * {{cite book |first1= C. Geoffrey|last1= Edge|first2= V. Bruce|last2= Irvine|authorlink= |title= A Practical Approach to the Appraisal of Capital Expenditures|url= |year= 1981|publisher= [[Society of Management Accountants of Canada]]|location= [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]]|isbn= 0-920212-29-8|edition=2nd|ref=harv}}<!--|accessdate= 26 February 2013--> * {{cite book |first1= Thomas E.|last1= Copeland|first2= J. Fred|last2= Weston|authorlink= |title= Financial Theory and Corporate Policy|url= |year= 1988|publisher= [[Addison-Wesley]]|location= [[Reading, Massachusetts|Reading]]|isbn= 0-201-10648-5|edition=3rd|ref=harv}}<!--|accessdate= 9 February 2015--> * {{cite journal |last= Jones|first= Thomas W.|last2= Smith|first2= J. David|date= 1982|title= An Historical Perspective of Net Present Value and Equivalent Annual Cost|url= http://umiss.lib.olemiss.edu:82/record=b1000787|journal= The Accounting Historians Journal|publisher= [[Academy of Accounting Historians]]|volume= 9|issue= 1|pages= 103{{endash}}110|ref=harv}} * {{cite journal|last1= Kauffmann|first1= Paul|last2= Howard|first2= Ed|last3= Yao|first3= Jason|last4= Harbinson|first4= Drew|last5= Brooks|first5= Newell|last6= Williams|first6= Richard|last7= Gurganus|first7= Christine |title = Criteria for Fleet Management: Identification of Optimal Disposal Points using Equivalent Uniform Annual Cost|journal = Transportation Research Record|issn= 0361-1981|url=http://docs.trb.org/prp/12-2637.pdf|doi = 10.3141/2292-20|date = 2012|volume= 2292|pages = 171{{endash}}178|publisher = [[Transportation Research Board]]}}
