{{Infobox book | name = The ITT Wars: An Insider's View of Hostile Takeovers | title_orig = | translator = | image = The ITT Wars -- bookcover.jpg | border = yes | caption = Softcover edition | author = [[Rand Araskog]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = Business history, [[ITT Corporation]] | genre = Non-fiction | publisher = [[Henry Holt & Co.]] | release_date = 1989 | english_release_date = | media_type = Print | pages = 241 pp. | isbn = 978-1893122383 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The ITT Wars: An Insider's View of Hostile Takeovers''''' is a non-fiction book about [[ITT Corporation]] written by its CEO [[Rand Araskog]]. The book was published by [[Henry Holt & Co.]] in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/The-ITT-Wars-Insiders-Takeovers/dp/1893122387|publisher=[[amazon.com]]|title = The ITT Wars: An Insider's View of Hostile Takeovers|accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2417685.The_ITT_Wars?from_search=true&search_version=service|publisher=[[goodreads.com]]|title=The ITT Wars: An Insider's View of Hostile Takeovers |accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beardbooks.com/beardbooks/the_itt_wars.html|publisher=beardbooks.com|title=The ITT Wars: An Insider's View of Hostile Takeovers by Rand V. Araskog |accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref>
==Contents== The book chronicles a [[hostile takeover]] attempt by [[Jay Pritzker]] to get control over the corporation.
==Review== {{quote|The book as a whole is a self-serving account of fighting takeover and board-room battles and taking on the French bureaucracy in a joint venture involving ITT`s telecommunications operations in Europe. It is written in a breezy, first-person style, a la [[Lee Iacocca|Iacocca]], that attempts to bring the reader close to the world of business negotiation and intrigue.
There also is an interesting account, skimpy in detail, of how Araskog succeeded in persuading former Defense Secretary [[Caspar Weinberger]] not to deny classified information to an ITT German subsidiary, [[Standard Eletrik Lorenz]]. A Soviet defector had identified the firm as a source of leaks, but Araskog said the information was false. Weinberger was ready to make the ITT firm an example, but backed off when his aide, [[Richard Perle]], launched a probe that supported ITT.}}
—Review by ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-04-02/business/8903310599_1_itt-stock-itt-breakup-rand-araskog|publisher=[[chicagotribune.com]]|title=Itt`s Araskog Takes Aim At Takeover Artists |first = William|last = Neikirk|accessdate=2015-07-03|date=1989-04-02}}</ref>
